Powered by RubiQube Ad Network LAGOS – The FIFA Women’s World Cup will kick off today, Friday, June 7 and end on Sunday, July 7 in France, with the host country play South Korea in the opening match. This will be the eighth edition of the quadrennial football championship contested by the women’s national teams of the member associations of the Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA). In March 2015, France won the right to host the event; the first time the country will host the tournament, and the third time a European nation will. Matches are planned for nine cities across France. The United States enters the competition as defending champions. It will also be the first Women’s World Cup to use the video assistant referee (VAR) system. The 24 teams taking part in the tournament have been grouped into six groups of four teams each. The teams are Australia, China PR, Japan, South Korea, and Thailand from Asia. Africa is represented by Nigeria, Cameroon and South Africa as CONCACAF three teams being Canada, Jamaica and United States. CONMEBOL also has three teams and they are Argentina, Brazil and Chile, while Oceanic Football Confederation (OFC) has one team in New Zealand. UEFA has the highest number of nine teams including England, France (hosts), Germany, Italy, Netherlands, Norway, Scotland, Spain and Sweden. Nigeria is in Group A with hosts France, Norway and South Korea.